  "body": "Code:\r\n\r\n```solidity\r\n// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT\r\npragma solidity 0.8.17;\r\n\r\ncontract Test {\r\n  bool private flag = true;\r\n  \r\n  modifier someModifier() {\r\n    require(flag, \"Failed in modifier\");\r\n    _;\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  function f() external someModifier {\r\n    require(false, \"Can't call this method\");\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nI disabled the optimizer, due to #2755, and wrote some test code, where I instantiate the `Test` contract as `contract`.\r\n\r\nIf I call the code using `await contract.f()`, I correctly get:\r\n\r\n```\r\n     Error: VM Exception while processing transaction: reverted with reason string 'Can't call this method'\r\n      at Test.f (contracts/Test.sol:13)\r\n      at processTicksAndRejections (node:internal/process/task_queues:96:5)\r\n      at runNextTicks (node:internal/process/task_queues:65:3)\r\n      at listOnTimeout (node:internal/timers:528:9)\r\n      at processTimers (node:internal/timers:502:7)\r\n      at async HardhatNode._mineBlockWithPendingTxs (node_modules/hardhat/src/internal/hardhat-network/provider/node.ts:1805:23)\r\n      at async HardhatNode.mineBlock (node_modules/hardhat/src/internal/hardhat-network/provider/node.ts:494:16)\r\n      at async EthModule._sendTransactionAndReturnHash (node_modules/hardhat/src/internal/hardhat-network/provider/modules/eth.ts:1522:18)\r\n```\r\n\r\nHowever, if I call the code using `await expect(contract.f()).to.be.revertedWith(\"Some wrong revert message\")`, then I don't see the `Test.f` frame in the stacktrace:\r\n\r\n```\r\n     AssertionError: Expected transaction to be reverted with reason 'Wrong revert message', but it reverted with reason 'Can't call this method'\r\n      at processTicksAndRejections (node:internal/process/task_queues:96:5)\r\n      at runNextTicks (node:internal/process/task_queues:65:3)\r\n      at listOnTimeout (node:internal/timers:528:9)\r\n      at processTimers (node:internal/timers:502:7)\r\n      at async Context.<anonymous> (test/index.js:30:5)\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis renders the stacktrace useless in the latter case.",
